  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3248593972" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3248593972" />
    <a title="T. Rahmaan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108483231-t-rahmaan"><img alt="T. Rahmaan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1578628392p2/108483231.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3248593972?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="T. Rahmaan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="T. Rahmaan" href="/user/show/108483231-t-rahmaan">T. Rahmaan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781451631579" href="/book/show/10938062-manchild-in-the-promised-land">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3248593972" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9441245630101740483">Claude Brown, like so many of the &quot;first Northern generation of Negroes,” had been given the impossible task of actualizing the deferred dreams of his parents. If the Great Migration signified a physical exodus from the throes of the Jim Crow South, the refugee children spawned from that flight grappled with the challenge of forming their own identity amongst disparate realities. They&apos;d inherited the same racist exploitation as their forebears, yet they also bore the unrealistic expectations of </span>
  <span id="freeText9441245630101740483" style="display:none">Claude Brown, like so many of the "first Northern generation of Negroes,” had been given the impossible task of actualizing the deferred dreams of his parents. If the Great Migration signified a physical exodus from the throes of the Jim Crow South, the refugee children spawned from that flight grappled with the challenge of forming their own identity amongst disparate realities. They'd inherited the same racist exploitation as their forebears, yet they also bore the unrealistic expectations of an entire Black generation before them, a generation who'd hoped for a promised land but was left disappointed because they couldn't afford to pay the rent. Trapped within a century-cycle he neither understood or appreciated, Brown, fittingly, began his story with movement, his own youthful migration heralded by the simple call to "Run!" <br /><br />Brown, like so many Black boys of his era, left his stoop early, rounding the corners of convention and measuring himself in (stolen) dollars and cents before breaking free of "the Man" and somehow finding his way back home. Yet very few realized in those early days that the streets themselves were a trap, every corner a pitfall that could pull one into the deep and rarely, if ever, let go. Indeed, Brown wrote, "I always thought of Harlem as home, but I never thought of Harlem as being a house. To me, home was the streets." <br /><br />Those same streets gave meaning to the children within that first Northern generation. It gave them voices and (nick)names. It gave them a sense of power and a means of characterization and stratification, a sorting of themselves in the natural formation of community. It gave them escape and entertainment, as there was always something to do. It even gave them a private culture, a lens by which to reexamine their immediate world and appropriate new traditions, values, and definitions. In this way, all women became "bitches,” Brown could easily understand the differences between a "prostitute" and a "whore,” and an unsuspecting fool could become someone's "trick." In this way, too, these desperate yet disillusioned Black children became criminals and junkies.<br /><br />Throughout the book, I felt the confusion a child of the street must realize while enduring the labor of rectification. The labor of separating the north from the south as one does a lie from the truth. The labor of building a sense of righteous manhood when the men in Harlem are only idolized as hustlers on a Murphy or ex-cons selling heroin. The labor of rectifying blood bonds and family ties, especially when your kid brother is the junkie whose blood mixes with heroin in an overused syringe. The labor of beautifying Blackness when, as Brown wrote, "most of the [Black] girls seemed crude and harsh. They were chicks who you couldn't be but so sweet to, because they weren't sweet themselves." <br /><br />Though not an ambitious writer, Brown tells his ambitious story authentically and authoritatively. It's blunt, the sentences short and simple. It's brutal, the recollections mostly deviant and unapologetic. The men are largely an assorted cast of myopic types who’re satiated by Saturday night, their urges fed by sex, money, and drugs. The women are mostly broken-hearted lovers or mothers, collateral damage in the never-ending war men waged for the next score. <br /><br />Brown’s literary limitations are apparent, the wording redundant and the emotive arc sparse, the author most notably denying his readers a firm moment of metamorphosis. Or, perhaps, it was a confluence of events that changed Brown, the same as it was a confluence of events that shaped him. Perhaps, too, the writing itself is enough of an ascension, OUR reward being HIS ability to ruminate upon the life and times that made him. <br /><br />And Claude Brown had indeed made it. More specifically, just like the generation before him who’d fled the racist South, Brown, too, had made it "out" of the most overt forms of oppression that bound him. Yet so much humanity had been lost within the struggle. That, I suppose, is the underlying thrust of the book: it’s an homage to the humanity that can be shared like a bottle of wine among the disaffected and the downtrodden, those who perhaps wonder if their struggles are worth their battle scars and disappointments, those who may "RUN!" wild throughout an inner-city street, if only to survive the night and break free at dawn.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9441245630101740483" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

